PETER KLEIN:  You'll have to break it down into its components.
There's actually two pieces of the non-annuity business, of the transactional business, the Windows Server piece, and then the other pieces of the business.
The Windows Server non-annuity piece actually grew mid-teens, so tracked towards the hardware market.
The other products, things like SQL Server, and Visual Studio grew slower than that in anticipation of a product release that's coming up.
So, it tends to be less sort of correlated, particularly in quarters where there's a significant growth year-over-year.
So that was the issue there.
