So, that's why having this one team that think about Outlook.com as well as Exchange helps us think about those dual-users, the same thing with Files, and OneDrive, and OneDrive for Business, because we want to have the software have the smarts about separating out the state, caring about IT control and data protection, while me, as an end user, gets to have the experiences that I want.
That's how we are thinking about harmonizing those digital life and work experiences.
On the hardware side, we will continue to build hardware that fits with these experiences, if I understand your question right, which is how will we differentiate our first party hardware.
We will build first party hardware that's creating categories.
A good example is what we have done with Surface Pro 3.
